DOMAIN_OVERVIEW:
This domain encompasses feminist and communitarian critiques of atomistic
conceptions of autonomy and self-reliance. Relational autonomy theories,
developed primarily by feminist philosophers since the late 1980s, challenge
the view that autonomy requires independence from social relationships.
Instead, they argue that autonomy is constituted through—not despite—our
social embeddedness. Key debates include: (1) whether relational accounts
are causally or constitutively relational; (2) whether they are procedural
or substantive; (3) whether they risk paternalism by making oppressive social
conditions autonomy-undermining. Communitarian philosophers (Sandel, MacIntyre,
Taylor, Walzer) argue that liberal individualism neglects how communities shape
moral identities. Care ethicists (Held, Noddings) emphasize interdependence
and the moral significance of caring relationships, rejecting self-sufficiency
as an ideal. Recent work (Khader 2020) raises concerns that relational autonomy
may deny agency to oppressed people, while defenders (Humphries 2025, Mackenzie
2019) argue it better captures constraints on autonomy under oppression.

RELEVANCE_TO_PROJECT:
This domain provides critical counterbalance to individualistic DIY valorization.
If autonomy is constituted relationally, then self-reliance may not always be
valuable—dependence on others may be constitutive of autonomy rather than
threatening to it. Care ethics challenges the moral priority of independence.
Communitarian critiques suggest that DIY individualism may reflect problematic
atomistic self-conceptions. These views directly challenge whether "doing it
yourself" is morally superior to receiving help or relying on others.

NOTABLE_GAPS:
Limited direct engagement between relational autonomy literature and craft/DIY
practices. Most applications focus on bioethics, healthcare, and oppression.
Few papers explicitly address the moral value of self-reliance vs. mutual aid
in everyday contexts. The debate sometimes remains abstract; concrete examples
of when interdependence enhances autonomy (beyond healthcare) would strengthen
the literature. Seven entries lack abstracts (marked INCOMPLETE): foundational
edited collection Mackenzie & Stoljar 2000, Mackenzie 2019 overview, early
Nedelsky 1989 article, McLeod & Sherwin 2000 chapter, Stoljar 2017, Holroyd
2009, and Levy 2023. These remain in bibliography for reference but notes
provide sufficient context.

SYNTHESIS_GUIDANCE:
Emphasize the tension between relational and atomistic autonomy conceptions.
Distinguish causally relational (relationships support autonomy development)
from constitutively relational (relationships partly define autonomy). Note
internal debate: does relational autonomy risk paternalism (Khader) or better
diagnose constraints (Humphries)? Connect to DIY question: does self-reliance
reflect atomistic ideal? Can accepting help manifest autonomy?

KEY_POSITIONS:
- Relational autonomy (Mackenzie/Stoljar, Westlund, Friedman): 11 papers - Autonomy requires/is shaped by supportive social relationships
- Care ethics (Held, Noddings): 2 papers - Interdependence and care are morally fundamental, not threats to autonomy
- Communitarian critique (Sandel): 2 papers - Liberal individualism neglects constitutive communities
- Feminist critics of relational autonomy (Khader): 1 paper - Socially constitutive accounts risk paternalism toward oppressed agents
- Interdependence theorists: 2 papers - Autonomy and interdependence are compatible or mutually reinforcing
