  note = {
  CORE ARGUMENT: Friedman develops a relational conception of autonomy sensitive to gendered social contexts. She argues that traditional autonomy theory ignores how gender socialization and oppression constrain self-determination. Friedman defends autonomy as still valuable for women but argues it must be reconceived to acknowledge social embeddedness. She distinguishes her procedural relational account from substantive approaches, arguing agents can be autonomous even while endorsing oppressive norms if they reflectively endorse them.

